Lets suppose that potatos and corn are native to Europe.  What effects
might this have on Europe pre-1492?

I wonder if this would not increse the effeciency of northern European
agriculture, making northern Europe rather more populated.  Scotland
and Ireland and Sweden and Finland do relatively better.

Second, I wonder if this does not increase total population somewhat,
which strengthens the role of towns, makes the  industrial revolution
more likely, and makes disease more deadly.

Finally, I believe that corn is a *much* better animal feed per acre
than wheat or rye.  I would expect a Europe with corn to have more
domesticated animals than one without.

-Charles Talleyrand
</POST>
