Corn *is* native to Europe.

Check your dictionary, and look at the word's *origins* ...

[Origin: bef. 900; ME, OE; c. D koren, ON korn, G Korn, Goth kaúrn;
akin to L granum grain, Russ zernó]

"Before 900" is the clue. 1492 being the earliest possible contact
(definitively proved) of Europeans with *maize*.

http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=corn

What you *meant* to say, of course, is "Lets suppose that potatoes and
maize are native to Europe."

And, no, its not being pedantic, either - the use of Corn = Maize is
peculiar to North America (not that it is peculiar *in* North America,
or anywhere else, not the several possible meanings of "peculiar",
too) and this newsgroup is NOT peculiar to North America, it is
worldwide, so the wider meaning is more correct (IMO, FWIW).

Corn has a very long and well documented indo-european meaning that
does NOT equal it being Maize *necessarily* (note the "necessarily"
before flying off your perch).

Its presence in Europe changes *everything* on such a fundamental
basis that I don't know where to begin, especially if it is combined
in such presence with potatoes.

Suffice it to say that population growth and density would be faster
and higher than it was historically, *far* faster and *far* higher.

This means larger cities and, almost inevitably, quicker technological
innovation ... so European history looks *vastly* different on so many
levels that it is, as I said, really impossible to speculate in any
logical way because of the multitude of flow on PoDs.

