Average crop yields, of corn (Queen's English) in classical times were
on the order of 2:1 to 3:1. That is, for each kilo of seed corn, you
got between 2 and 3 kilos of return. Take away the one kilo you need
for next year's sowing and you get 1-2 kilos surplus.

For  Maize?

Yields are VERY high, a return of 70-80 kilos per kilo of seed sown
being the minimum in even the most marginal (semi-arid) areas, and
yields of 150 kilos are a bare minimum for good land.

Where incomplete climatic adaptation had been achieved, yields were
lower, but still attractive.

In perfect conditions, yields of up to 800 kilos return on a kilo of
seed were recorded in pre-modern times.

Based on the MINIMUM increase, you would gain a 30 fold increase in
food productivity, which means, of course, a 30 fold increase in the
population that could be supported.

The evidence from history of population growth following the adoption
of new crops and/or agricultural practices and technology show that
the population of a region increases to the limit of the expanded food
supply in around a century or so.

Imagine a Mediterranean world with a population and population density
greater than that of China after the adoption of wetlands rice with
2-3 growing seasons per year ... and you get the picture, sorta. Maize
is more productive even than Wetlands Rice.

