Wrong.

The limit on crop productivity is the yield per hectare
of land cultivated.

For instance:

in 1880, the US produced 1.7 billion bushels of maize from
62.5 million acres (27 bushels/acre), and 502 million bushels
of wheat from 38.1 million acres (13 bushels/acre).

At yield/seed ratios of 200 to 1 for maize and 2 to 1 for wheat,
the net harvest from maize would be 26.87 bushels/acre, while
the net for wheat would be 6.5 bushels/acre.

That's 4 to 1, not 30 to 1. Of that 4-to-1 gain, half is
greater yield per acre, and half is the 99% reduction
in yield diverted to next year's seed requirement.

Unless one has land going unsown for want of seed, the
benefit of increased yield per kilo of seed is limited
to that reduction. If the yield per seed kilo is even
2 kilos of grain, the maximum improvement is 100%.
