Umm. Your maths are off here. The yield for wheat and the like in
classical agriculture was c. 2-3:1. That is, 1 kilo of seed produced
2-3 kilos of grain. Of which 1 kilo had to be kept for next years
seed.

That means that you would have gotten, with *historically accurate*
yields for the earliest period, a surplus of 6.5 bushels per acre for
the low end and 8 bushels per acre for the high end.

The figures I cited for maize come from the original mesoamerican
origins, pre-dating (or immediately postdating) the Colombian exchange
and, presumably, unaffected by the introduction of eurasian advances
in cultivation, and so would remain the same.

Which would mean, at the very least, a *tripling* of yields.

I suspect the problem with your figures is that maize was incompletely
climatically adapted to the USA, which is a known problem, and one I
cited.

If it had been an *original* Eurasian crop, presumably from the Middle
East, then it could move east and west into similar climate zones,
which is what gave Eurasian agriculture a head start compared to its
American cousin (amongst other things) and, at worst, it would "soon"
have been climatically adapted as Wetlands rice (origins possibly in
Ceylon or Burma) was to China ... originally, not growing because the
growing season was too short, then, later, growing 2-3 crops per
season in the south and one, at least, further north.

