He would soon be disabused of the notion, 1 hectare of corn (european
usage) produced c. 3 hectoliters (c. 200 kilos each, or c. 600 kilos)
of grain for c. 1 hectoliter of seed by the 17th century. It took
around 3 hectoliters of corn (european usage) to feed one person for
one year ... so they would need around 1.5 ha per person just for
survival, and more than that to pay taxes etc.

There is evidence that the yield weight per hectoliter was also lower
in classical periods than it was in modern times, but it is uncertain
by how much ... just that it was "significant".

During the classical era, yields were around ONE THIRD of that (and,
depending on how far back into the classical era you go, may
effectively have required twice as much land, making yield per ha ONE
SIXTH of that).

And they get one crop per year.

Estimated *pre-columbian* yields of Maize in the valley of Mexico are
at least 3000 to 5000 kilos per hectare TWICE A YEAR.

Say 15-25 times more *per crop* ... gained *twice a year* ... or 30-50
times mor productive, based on a weight per hectoliter of 200 kilos
for corn (european) that only applies to the 17th century or later,
than "corn".

Now, your Egyptian peasant is actually a really, really, poor choice
for comparison purposes.

Egypt is atypical. For obvious reasons, I would have thought.

However, to explain.

The Nile floods. Every year. Fertilising and watering the land in one.

This makes the land vastly more productive than anywhere else, pretty
much, in Europe *FOR A START*.

But it gets better.

The climate means that the Egyptians typically got 2 or even 3 crops
per year on the same land.

So your example peasant will see, fairly quickly, the possibilities of
maize, its yield density etc. and, OK, *HE* will only get a lesser
yield, but the yields I cited for European grain production are
*averages* (so, yes, some lands were *really* marginal because of poor
conditions and short growing seasons), so in the rest of Europe, maize
will be amaizing.

